english:
  title: In Praise of Tao Yuanming
  author: Lee Gyu-bo
  language: eng
  text: |-
    I have read the biography and collected poems of Tao Yuanming, and grown fond of his broad and penetrating spirit. Thus I offer this praise:

    Upon a stringless lute,
    Dwell joy and contentment of heart—
    Yet people say, without strings,
    what use is a lute?
    A lute bereft of strings—
    where would its music arise?

    But if we speak of harboring intent,
    then all things are thus.
    Tao Yuanming loved wine,
    growing drunk day by day—
    yet a cup without wine,
    could it still bring intoxication?

    How can the vulgar comprehend
    the refined taste of an enlightened man?
    What must be preserved lies within;
    what may be discarded lies without.
    Should one covet only the external,
    then desire itself becomes the seed.
    Is it merely the lute's string alone?
    The endless grasping knows no satiation.

    Should one abandon what lies within,
    short life and early death come calling.
    The immortal sage distills the elixir
    to attain eternal life—
    yet wine, too, is a divine medicine;
    to forgo it invites affliction.

    Better to forget the lute's string
    than to part with wine.
  footnotes:
    - Tao Yuanming (陶淵明, 365-427) was a celebrated Eastern Jin poet and recluse known for his love of wine and his rejection of worldly ambition.
    - The stringless lute and the cup without wine are metaphors for the pursuit of meaning beyond external form—the Daoist principle of finding essence in apparent emptiness.
    - The 'immortal sage' (真人) and 'divine medicine' (神藥) reference both Daoist alchemy and the philosophical understanding of wine as a path to spiritual transcendence.
